    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-01-08T19:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-01-08T19:00:00-05:00" n="179"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d179">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">837.61351/2372: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Cuba</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Beaulac</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Habana</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-01-08T19:00:00-05:00"
                            >January 8, 1941—7 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received January 9—12:50 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>11. From Pierson<note n="35" xml:id="d179fn35">Warren Lee Pierson, President of
                        the Export-Import Bank.</note> to Will Clayton.<note n="36"
                        xml:id="d179fn36">Deputy Federal Loan Administrator.</note> It is
                    anticipated that the Cuban Government will fix a crop of 2,000,000 Spanish long
                    tons <pb facs="0237" n="229" xml:id="pg_229"/> exclusive of any extraordinary
                    quota which may be financed by the Export-Import Bank. On the basis of a crop of
                    this size, I recommend that the bank offer to finance the production during 1941
                    of a special additional quota of 400,000 tons the financing to be made at the
                    rate of one cent per pound upon the following conditions:</p>
                <p>Loan to be against 5-year notes secured by pledge of sugar as well as allocation
                    of 6 cents per bag production tax and provision for diversion of not exceeding
                    50,000 tons of pledged sugar per annum for sale in the American market within
                    the American quota if equivalent amount is not sold elsewhere at price not lower
                    than the financing price.</p>
                <p>Authorization for the financing should be obtained from the Cuban Congress which
                    should include in the enabling legislation provision for the extension without
                    substantial modification of Decree Law 522.<note n="37" xml:id="d179fn37"
                        >Promulgated January 18, 1936. The decree established standards for the
                        production and export of sugar and authorized Government regulation; see <hi
                            rend="italic">Gaceta Oficial</hi>, Edicion Extraordinaria No. 13,
                        January 20, 1936.</note>
                </p>
                <p>It is contemplated that the Cuban Sugar Stabilization Institute<note n="38"
                        xml:id="d179fn38">A governmental body organized to supervise the production
                        and export of sugar, authorized on May 14, 1931, and continued by the Decree
                        Law 522.</note> would act as representative of the parties to the financing
                    agreement and that a private bank would act as trustee.</p>
                <p>If the foregoing is approved by the State Department and the bank I shall submit
                    it to the Cuban Government at the first opportunity. [Pierson.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Beaulac</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
